<subSubSection pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1436,911,1796]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,911,937]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Remarks:</emphasis>
The excellent figures of 
<taxonomicName authority="Denis, 1951" authorityName="Denis" authorityYear="1951" box="[581,1015,912,938]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Erigonopterna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alticeps">
<emphasis box="[581,858,912,937]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Erigonopterna alticeps</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Denis, J." box="[867,1015,912,938]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="245 - 258" refId="ref43730" refString="Denis, J. (1951) Captures d'araignees halophiles et hygrophiles. Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique de France, 56, 147 - 152. Denis, J. (1957) Araignees du massif calcaire des Eaux-Bonnes (Basses-Pyrenees). Bulletin de la Societe d' Histoire Naturelle de Toulouse, 92, 245 - 258." type="journal article" year="1951">Denis, 1951</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, with typical cephalic tubercle and tibial apophysis allow a positive identification as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Simon 1881)" baseAuthorityName="Simon" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[780,1281,949,975]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Trichopterna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cucurbitina">
<emphasis box="[780,1095,949,974]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Trichopterna cucurbitina</emphasis>
(Simon 1881)
</taxonomicName>
. The former becomes its junior synonym. Denis statement “à un examen superficielle, cette Araignée peut être confondue avec 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Westring" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[212,457,1024,1049]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Trichopterna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thorelli">
<emphasis box="[212,457,1024,1049]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Trichopterna thorelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Westring,)” also is confirm to the synonymy.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1436,911,1796]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,353,1061,1087]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Description:</emphasis>
Male: Measurements: Total length 2.2; prosoma 0.64 long, 0.50 wide. Colour: Prosoma orange brown, margin suffused with grey; legs orange brown, patellae yellowish brown; abdomen grey. Prosoma (
<figureCitation box="[270,437,1136,1162]" captionStart="FIGURES 118–131" captionStartId="56.[151,272,1841,1865]" captionText="FIGURES 118–131. Figs 118–124. Trichopterna cucurbitina (Simon, 1881); 118. Male prosoma, lateral view; 119. Idem, dorsal view; 120. Male palp, prolateral view; 121. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 122. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 123. Epigynum; 124. Vulva. Figs 125–131. Walckenaeria dalmasi (Simon, 1914); 125. Male prosoma, lateral view; 126. Cephalic tubercle, lateral view; 127. Male palp, prolateral view; 128. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 129. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 130. Epigynum, ventral view; 131. Vulva, ventral view." pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Figs 118, 119</figureCitation>
): With distinct, rounded tubercle carrying the posterior median eyes; with concavity above the anterior median eyes, and with small sulcus behind the lateral eyes. Legs: No tibial spines; Tb Mt I = 0.35, Tb Mt IV absent. Palp (
<figureCitation box="[517,685,1210,1236]" captionStart="FIGURES 118–131" captionStartId="56.[151,272,1841,1865]" captionText="FIGURES 118–131. Figs 118–124. Trichopterna cucurbitina (Simon, 1881); 118. Male prosoma, lateral view; 119. Idem, dorsal view; 120. Male palp, prolateral view; 121. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 122. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 123. Epigynum; 124. Vulva. Figs 125–131. Walckenaeria dalmasi (Simon, 1914); 125. Male prosoma, lateral view; 126. Cephalic tubercle, lateral view; 127. Male palp, prolateral view; 128. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 129. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 130. Epigynum, ventral view; 131. Vulva, ventral view." pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Figs 120–122</figureCitation>
): Tibia with large, triangular, retrolateral apophysis; protegulum strongly protruding; embolic division elongated, with spiral, gently narrowing embolus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1436,911,1796]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,299,1285,1311]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Female:</emphasis>
Measurements: Total length 2.6–2.7; prosoma 0.64–0.72 long, 0.52–0.62 wide. Prosoma unmodified. Legs: Spine formula 1111; L spI = L spiv = 1, P SpI = 0.14. Epigynum (
<figureCitation box="[1193,1301,1322,1348]" captionStart="FIGURES 118–131" captionStartId="56.[151,272,1841,1865]" captionText="FIGURES 118–131. Figs 118–124. Trichopterna cucurbitina (Simon, 1881); 118. Male prosoma, lateral view; 119. Idem, dorsal view; 120. Male palp, prolateral view; 121. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 122. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 123. Epigynum; 124. Vulva. Figs 125–131. Walckenaeria dalmasi (Simon, 1914); 125. Male prosoma, lateral view; 126. Cephalic tubercle, lateral view; 127. Male palp, prolateral view; 128. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 129. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 130. Epigynum, ventral view; 131. Vulva, ventral view." pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 123</figureCitation>
): With two slightly converging lateral grooves and two anteromedian, strongly chitinised lobes.Vulva (
<figureCitation box="[1310,1422,1360,1386]" captionStart="FIGURES 118–131" captionStartId="56.[151,272,1841,1865]" captionText="FIGURES 118–131. Figs 118–124. Trichopterna cucurbitina (Simon, 1881); 118. Male prosoma, lateral view; 119. Idem, dorsal view; 120. Male palp, prolateral view; 121. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 122. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 123. Epigynum; 124. Vulva. Figs 125–131. Walckenaeria dalmasi (Simon, 1914); 125. Male prosoma, lateral view; 126. Cephalic tubercle, lateral view; 127. Male palp, prolateral view; 128. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 129. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 130. Epigynum, ventral view; 131. Vulva, ventral view." pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 124</figureCitation>
): Spermathecae oblique oval, with some additional lobes, touching in the middle; insemination ducts originating near anteromedian lobes, leading laterally to spermathecae.
</paragraph>
